# 2d random walk state space model
dim = 2
Nt = 250

# if no priors are passed, they're generated automatically
rw = tslib.inference.sts.RandomWalk(
    dim=dim,
    Nt=Nt,
)
# alternatively, can pass random variables or fixed tensors
rw2 = tslib.inference.sts.RandomWalk(
    dim=dim,
    Nt=Nt,
    mu=torch.zeros(1),
    vol=torch.ones(1),
)

fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(10, 5))
for path, path2 in zip(rw(), rw2()):  
    axes[0].plot(path)
    axes[1].plot(path2)
    
_ = axes[0].set_title("Auto priors")
_ = axes[1].set_title("User-set priors")

# generate some fake data and fit rw params to it
# we have a generative model so just use it to generate fake data...
dgp = tslib.inference.sts.RandomWalk(
    dim=dim, 
    Nt=Nt, 
    mu=torch.tensor(0.15), 
    vol=torch.tensor(0.5)
)
observed_data = dgp.prior_predictive()

inference_model = tslib.inference.sts.RandomWalk(
    dim=dim,
    Nt=Nt,
)
guide, losses = inference_model.fit(
    observed_data,
    verbosity=250,
    n_iterations=1500
)
plt.plot(losses)

# able to compose blocks arbitrarily (subject to geometric constraints e.g. positivity)
dim = 2
Nt = 250

# local linear trend model -- quadratic divergence, i.e. doubly integrated white noise
llt_mu = tslib.inference.sts.RandomWalk(dim=dim, Nt=Nt)
llt_rw = tslib.inference.sts.RandomWalk(dim=dim, Nt=Nt, mu=llt_mu)
# the compute graph is implicit -- only need to operate on last block (which is likelihood fn)
llt_prior = llt_rw()

# periodic colored noise
alpha = tslib.inference.sts.DiscreteSeasonal(dim=dim, Nt=Nt, n_seasons=100)
ar1 = tslib.inference.sts.AR1(dim=dim, Nt=Nt, alpha=alpha)
ar1_prior = ar1.prior_predictive()

# easy to create flexible exotic distributions
# this is a seasonal stochastic volatility variance gamma process constained to lie in (-1, 1)
# we're using arbitrary functions changing geometry of base distributions in apply_funcs
# ours are differentiable, but this isn't required for inference thanks to trace ELBO implementation in pyro
vg_mu = tslib.inference.sts.DiscreteSeasonal(
    dim=dim,
    Nt=Nt,
    n_seasons=7
)
vg_vol = tslib.inference.sts.ConstantCoefficientSDE(
    dim=dim,
    Nt=Nt,
    apply_funcs=(lambda x: torch.exp(x) / 365,)
)
vg_sde = tslib.inference.sts.ConstantCoefficientSDE(
    dim=dim,
    Nt=Nt,
    mu=vg_mu,
    vol=vg_vol,
    dt=None,
    obs_sd=torch.tensor(0.01),  # explicitly set state space uncertainty
    apply_funcs=(torch.tanh,)
)
vg_prior = vg_sde.prior_predictive()

fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize=(15, 5))
for a, prior, name in zip(axes, [llt_prior, ar1_prior, vg_prior], ['LLT', 'seasonal AR1', 'VG']):
    a.plot(prior.squeeze().T)
    a.set_title(name)

# cross-covariance functionals

fig, axes = plt.subplots(*seasonal.cov_func.shape[:2], figsize=(10, 10))

    for matrix, ax in zip(row, ax_row):

# another extremely useful functional: taking expectations
# option pricing reduces to a few lines of code
# price an option under a similar vg process as above, this one in (0, 1) (corresponds to election option)
dim = 1
election_vol = tslib.inference.sts.ConstantCoefficientSDE(
    dim=dim,
    Nt=Nt,
    apply_funcs=(lambda x: torch.exp(x) / 365,)
)
election_sde = tslib.inference.sts.ConstantCoefficientSDE(
    dim=dim,
    Nt=Nt,
    mu=torch.tensor(0.1),
    vol=election_vol,
    dt=None,
    obs_sd=torch.tensor(0.01),
    apply_funcs=(lambda x: 1./(1. + torch.exp(-x)),)
)
election_prior = election_sde.prior_predictive()
plt.plot(election_prior.squeeze())

option_payoff = lambda x, strike: torch.where(x[..., -1].squeeze() > strike, torch.ones(1), torch.zeros(1))
n_vals = 98
strikes = torch.linspace(0.01, 0.99, n_vals)
values = torch.empty(n_vals)

for i, strike in enumerate(strikes):
    values[i] = election_sde.expect(
        lambda x: option_payoff(x, strike),
        n_forecast=365,
        n_inner_sim=25,
        n_outer_sim=50
    )

# Sanity check: the naive equity asset price model, we know what value as a function of strike looks like
geo_sde = tslib.inference.sts.ConstantCoefficientSDE(
    dim=dim,
    Nt=Nt,
    dt=torch.tensor(0.01),
    mu=0.1 * torch.ones(1),
    vol=torch.ones(1),
    obs_sd=0.05 * torch.ones(1),
    apply_funcs=(torch.exp,)
)

option_payoff = lambda x, strike: torch.where(
    x[..., -1].squeeze() > strike,
    x[..., -1].squeeze() - strike, 
    torch.zeros(1)
)
n_vals = 98
strikes = torch.linspace(0.01, 2.0, n_vals)
values = torch.empty(n_vals)

for i, strike in enumerate(strikes):
    values[i] = election_sde.expect(
        lambda x: option_payoff(x, strike),
        n_forecast=252,
        n_inner_sim=25,
        n_outer_sim=50
    )

# demo (simple) use case on some financial data
# infer latent parameters of short rate model for german 10yr bond
# then forecast years into the future
BUND_CODE = "IRLTLT01DEM156N"
bund = web.DataReader(
    BUND_CODE,
    'fred',
    datetime.datetime(2000, 1, 1),
    datetime.datetime(2020, 1, 1),
)
dt = torch.tensor(1./12)  # monthly frequency, measure time in years
date = '2010-01-01'
time = torch.linspace(0, (len(bund) - 1) * dt.numpy(), len(bund))
train_ind = len(bund.loc[:date])

train = torch.tensor(bund.loc[:date].values, dtype=torch.float) \
    .unsqueeze(dim=0).squeeze(dim=-1)
test = torch.tensor(bund.loc[date:].values, dtype=torch.float) \
    .unsqueeze(dim=0).squeeze(dim=-1)

ar1 = tslib.inference.sts.AR1(dim=1, Nt=train.shape[-1])
short_rate_model = tslib.inference.sts.RandomWalk(
    dim=1,
    Nt=train.shape[-1],
    mu=ar1,
    x0=train[..., 0],
    ls_rv=True,
)

In [16]:
posterior_predictive = short_rate_model.posterior(
    guide,
    train,
    size=1000
)["_RETURN"]
posterior_forecast = short_rate_model.posterior_forecast(
    guide,
    train,
    size=1000,
    n_steps_ahead=bund.loc[:date].values.flatten().shape[0]
)

post_mean = posterior_predictive.mean(dim=0).squeeze()
post_std = posterior_predictive.std(dim=0).squeeze()
forecast_mean = posterior_forecast.mean(dim=0).squeeze()
forecast_std = posterior_forecast.std(dim=0).squeeze()
In [17]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots()

ax.plot(time[:train_ind], train.squeeze(), color='k', label='train')
ax.plot(time[:train_ind], post_mean, color='red')

ax.fill_between(
    time[:train_ind],
    post_mean - post_std,
    post_mean + post_std,
    alpha=0.25,
    color='red'
)
ax.fill_between(
    time[:train_ind],
    post_mean - 2. * post_std,
    post_mean + 2. * post_std,
    alpha=0.25,
    color='red',
    label='predictive'
)

ax.plot(time[train_ind - 1:], test.squeeze(), color='k', linestyle='--', label='test')
ax.plot(time[train_ind - 1:], forecast_mean, color='blue')

ax.fill_between(
    time[train_ind - 1:],
    forecast_mean - forecast_std,
    forecast_mean + forecast_std,
    alpha=0.25,
    color='blue'
)
ax.fill_between(
    time[train_ind - 1:],
    forecast_mean - 2. * forecast_std,
    forecast_mean + 2. * forecast_std,
    alpha=0.25,
    color='blue',
    label='forecast'
)
ax.tick_params(labelsize=15)
ax.set_xlabel('Time (years since 2000)', fontsize=15)
ax.set_ylabel('Interest rate (%)', fontsize=15)
